      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, let's focus on the accounting entries. In the first year, you would make a journal entry that debits Depreciation Expense and credits Accumulated Depreciation. Here’s the specific entry for your machinery:\n\n| Date | Account | Debit | Credit |\n|------|---------|-------|--------|\n| Jan 1 | Depreciation Expense | 9,000 | |\n| Jan 1 | Accumulated Depreciation | | 9,000 |\n\nThis entry records the expense for the year and accumulates the depreciation in a contra‑asset account. Over the five years, you’ll make this same entry each year, gradually reducing the machine’s book value from 50,000 to 5,000. The 45,000 total depreciation is split evenly, so each year you “use up” 9,000 of the asset’s value. This way, the income statement shows the expense, and the balance sheet shows the remaining book value.",
